<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>Define Accounting. What is its basic purpose?</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Accounting</span> is defined as <em>"the art of recording, classifying and summarizing in a significant manner and in terms of money, transactions and events which are of financial character and interpreting the results thereof."</em><br><br>
    It is also defined as <em>"the process of identifying, measuring, and communicating economic information to permit informed judgements and decisions."</em><br><br>
    <strong>Basic Purpose:</strong> Accounting is the <em>language of business</em>. Its purpose is to communicate the results of business operations to stakeholders so they can make sound decisions.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">2</div>What is Forensic Accounting? Write its steps.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Forensic Accounting</span> is the art of investigation over accounting records, financial statements, and related financial records. Its results are used for <strong>legal support and conflict resolution</strong>. It covers fraud, crime, insurance claims, and shareholder disputes.<br><br>
    <strong>Two Main Steps:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li><strong>Investigation:</strong> Collect evidence, identify red flags/discrepancies, interview staff, form a hypothesis about fraud, and recommend next actions.</li>
      <li><strong>Reporting:</strong> Present findings, determine how fraud occurred, suggest corrective steps and internal security improvements, then prepare for court proceedings.</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>Uses:</strong> Bank frauds, SEBI insider trading, shell companies, insolvency cases.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">3</div>What is Carbon Accounting?</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Carbon Accounting</span> is the practice of making scientifically robust and verifiable measurements of Greenhouse Gas (GHG) emissions.<br><br>
    <strong>Main Objective:</strong> To identify the carbon-density of areas, providing information for <em>low carbon impact land use planning</em>.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">4</div>Differentiate: Recordative, Interpretative, and Auditive functions of Accounting.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Function</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Who Does It</th></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Recordative</strong></td><td>Routine recording and classified posting of financial transactions in journals and ledgers</td><td>Accounts staff (manual/mechanical/electronic)</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Interpretative</strong></td><td>Analytical work – budget analysis, performance evaluation, funds flow analysis, decision support reports</td><td>Management Accountants / Controllers</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Auditive</strong></td><td>Verification and authentication of accounting statements and financial records</td><td>Public (external) accountants or Internal Auditors</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">5</div>What is Carbon Accounting? (Short Note)</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    Carbon accounting measures GHG emissions scientifically to guide low-carbon land use. Forensic accounting investigates financial records for legal purposes. Both are <em>emerging roles</em> showing how accounting expands beyond traditional bookkeeping.
  </div>
</div>

