<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>Discuss the Scope of Accounting with a neat diagram.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    The scope of accounting covers four main activities:<br><br>
    <strong>1. Data Creation & Collection (Historic & Predictive):</strong><br>
    Collects financial and economic transaction data. Traditionally historic (past transactions), but now includes predictive data for future planning.<br><br>
    <strong>2. Data Recording (Recordative Work):</strong><br>
    Recording in journals and ledgers per accounting theory. Can be manual, mechanical, or electronic (computers). This is the most time-consuming part.<br><br>
    <strong>3. Data Evaluation (Analytical & Auditive Work):</strong><br>
    <ul class="list">
      <li><em>Budgetary Control:</em> Controlling activities using budgets and standard costs.</li>
      <li><em>Performance Analysis:</em> Evaluating business performance.</li>
      <li><em>Funds Flow Analysis:</em> Tracking movement of funds.</li>
      <li><em>Internal Auditing:</em> Continuous watch over financial flows.</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>4. Data Reporting (External & Internal):</strong><br>
    <ul class="list">
      <li><em>External:</em> Financial statements (P&L, Balance Sheet) for shareholders, government.</li>
      <li><em>Internal:</em> Management reports for decision-making.</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="tip-box"><strong>Key Point:</strong> Accounting Theory sits at the CENTER of the scope diagram, governing all activities. The central purpose is <em>periodic matching of costs (efforts) and revenues (accomplishments).</em></div>
  </div>
</div>

