<div id="unit2" class="unit-header" style="border-left-color: var(--accent2);">
  <div class="unit-num" style="color:var(--accent2)">Unit 2</div>
  <h2>Accounting Concepts and Standards</h2>
</div>

<!-- CONCEPT QUICK REFERENCE -->
<div class="warn-box"><strong>📌 Quick Memory Aid – 10 Key Accounting Concepts:</strong><br>
BE – MM – CC – GP – AC – MA – CO – PER – OBJ – FD<br>
<em>(Business Entity, Money Measurement, Cost Concept, Going Concern, Accrual, Matching, Conservatism, Periodicity, Objectivity, Full Disclosure)</em></div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m5">5 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>Explain the Business Entity Concept.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Business Entity Concept:</span> Accounting treats the business and its owner(s) as <strong>two separate entities</strong>.<br><br>
    <strong>Implications:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>All accounting is done from the <em>business viewpoint</em>, not the owner's viewpoint.</li>
      <li>If the owner takes cash out for personal use → debit Drawings A/c (reduces capital), not an expense.</li>
      <li>If the owner brings cash in → the business has a <em>liability</em> to return it (it is capital).</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="tip-box">A limited company is a <em>separate legal entity</em> by law. This concept is harder to apply in sole proprietorship and partnership but the accountant must still maintain the distinction.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">2</div>Explain the Money Measurement Concept with its limitations.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Money Measurement Concept:</span> Only transactions that can be <strong>expressed in money terms</strong> are recorded in accounting.<br><br>
    Money acts as a "common denominator" to measure all assets and equities.<br><br>
    <strong>Limitations:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Cannot capture <em>qualitative aspects</em> – employee morale, customer satisfaction, management quality, interpersonal conflicts.</li>
      <li>Ignores <em>time value of money</em> – treats ₹1 today = ₹1 ten years ago (ignores inflation, forex fluctuations).</li>
      <li>Does not record non-monetary events like new R&D product acceptance by customers.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">3</div>What is the Conservatism Concept? Give an example.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Conservatism (Prudence) Concept:</span> <em>"Anticipate no profit; provide for all possible losses."</em><br><br>
    <strong>Rules:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Recognize revenue/gains only when <em>actually realised</em> (cash or legally enforceable debt).</li>
      <li>Provide for all known and <em>probable losses</em> immediately.</li>
      <li>Value inventory at <strong>lower of cost or market price</strong>.</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>Example:</strong> A court case is filed against the company – even if the outcome is unknown, the company must <em>create a provision for the possible loss</em> in its financial statements.<br><br>
    <div class="warn-box">Over-conservatism leads to false data. Rational use is advocated.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">4</div>What is the Cost Concept?</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Cost Concept:</span> An asset is recorded in books of accounts at the <strong>price paid to acquire it</strong> (historical cost), not at market value.<br><br>
    <strong>Example:</strong> Machinery purchased for ₹40,000 is shown in books at ₹40,000 even if its market value is ₹70,000.<br><br>
    <strong>Linked to:</strong> This concept conflicts with revaluation. The accounting profession sometimes allows revaluation when the difference between historical cost and market value is too large to ignore (for transparent Balance Sheets).
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">5</div>Explain GAAP and its three criteria.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">GAAP (Generally Accepted Accounting Principles)</span> is a framework of conventions, rules, and procedures that define standard accounting practices.<br><br>
    <strong>Three Criteria for Acceptance of any Accounting Principle:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Criterion</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Relevance</td><td>Results in meaningful / useful information for users</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Objectivity</td><td>Not influenced by personal bias; verifiable and trustworthy</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Feasibility</td><td>Can be implemented without undue complexity or cost</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m10">10 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>Explain all the Accounting Concepts to be observed at the Recording Stage.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <div class="concept-grid">
      <div class="concept-box">
        <h4>1. Business Entity Concept</h4>
        <p>Business and owner are separate. All entries from business viewpoint only.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="concept-box">
        <h4>2. Money Measurement Concept</h4>
        <p>Only monetary transactions recorded. Non-monetary events (loyalty, morale) excluded.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="concept-box">
        <h4>3. Cost Concept</h4>
        <p>Assets recorded at historical cost (acquisition price), not market value.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="concept-box">
        <h4>4. Going Concern Concept</h4>
        <p>Business is assumed to continue indefinitely. Assets valued at cost, not liquidation value.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="concept-box">
        <h4>5. Dual Aspect Concept</h4>
        <p>Every transaction has two aspects. Basis of Double Entry System.<br>Assets = Liabilities + Capital</p>
      </div>
      <div class="concept-box">
        <h4>6. Objectivity Principle</h4>
        <p>Only verifiable, fact-based information recorded. Reduces personal bias.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="tip-box"><strong>Memory Tip:</strong> "BE-MM-CC-GC-DA-OBJ" = Business Entity, Money Measurement, Cost Concept, Going Concern, Dual Aspect, Objectivity</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">2</div>Explain all the Accounting Concepts to be observed at the Reporting Stage.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Concept</th><th>Key Rule</th><th>Example</th></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Accrual Concept</strong></td><td>Recognize income when earned, expenses when incurred – regardless of cash receipt/payment</td><td>Salary due but not paid → still record as expense</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Matching Concept</strong></td><td>Match revenues and expenses of the <em>same period</em></td><td>Cost of goods SOLD (not produced) is matched to sales revenue</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Realisation Concept</strong></td><td>Revenue recognized only when <em>actually realized</em> (sale complete)</td><td>Probable order of ₹5 lakh NOT recorded as sales</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Periodicity Concept</strong></td><td>Divide business life into defined time periods (usually 1 year). Prepare statements for each.</td><td>Annual reports, quarterly MIS reports</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Conservatism Concept</strong></td><td>"Anticipate no profit, provide for all losses." Value stock at lower of cost or market price.</td><td>Provision for doubtful debts created even before confirmed</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Consistency Concept</strong></td><td>Same accounting method used from period to period. No arbitrary changes.</td><td>If FIFO used for inventory, must use FIFO every year</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Materiality Concept</strong></td><td>Events of <em>small importance</em> need not get theoretical treatment. Minor items can be expensed directly.</td><td>A ₹50 pencil can be expensed directly rather than capitalised</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Full Disclosure Concept</strong></td><td>All material facts disclosed in financial statements. Footnotes must be provided.</td><td>Contingent liabilities disclosed in notes to accounts</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m20">20 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>What are Accounting Standards? Explain the need, benefits, and India's accounting standards scenario. Also explain IFRS and its benefits/challenges.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <strong>I. Accounting Standards – Definition:</strong><br>
    Accounting Standards are <em>written policy documents</em> issued by expert accounting bodies that establish rules for recognition, measurement, treatment, and disclosure of accounting transactions, to ensure <strong>uniformity, comparability, and transparency</strong> in financial statements.<br><br>
    <strong>II. Need for Accounting Standards:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Different companies used different methods → misleading comparisons</li>
      <li>Investors and creditors need reliable, comparable information</li>
      <li>Prevent creative / manipulative accounting</li>
      <li>Facilitate cross-border investment and trade</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>III. Benefits of Accounting Standards:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Uniformity in financial reporting</li>
      <li>Builds investor confidence</li>
      <li>Reduces fraud and window dressing</li>
      <li>Facilitates inter-firm and international comparisons</li>
      <li>Helps auditors form opinions easily</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>IV. Indian Accounting Standards (Ind AS):</strong><br>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Issued by the <strong>Institute of Chartered Accountants of India (ICAI)</strong></li>
      <li>India has converged its standards with IFRS (called <em>Ind AS</em>)</li>
      <li>Applicable to listed companies and companies above certain thresholds</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>V. IFRS – International Financial Reporting Standards:</strong><br>
    IFRS are designed as a <em>common global language of business</em> so that accounts of companies are <strong>understandable and comparable across international boundaries</strong>.<br><br>
    <strong>Need for Convergence:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Companies expand internationally → need globally comparable financial statements</li>
      <li>Removes language and accounting barriers in global trade</li>
      <li>Attracts foreign investment</li>
    </ul>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Benefits of IFRS</th><th>Challenges of IFRS</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Global comparability of financial statements</td><td>Costly transition from existing standards</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Reduces cost for multinational companies</td><td>Requires training of accounting professionals</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Attracts foreign investors</td><td>Different legal/tax systems across countries</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Increases transparency and investor confidence</td><td>Some IFRS are complex and principle-based (subjectivity)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Facilitates cross-border mergers and acquisitions</td><td>May not suit needs of all countries equally</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

