<div id="unit3" class="unit-header" style="border-left-color: var(--accent3);">
  <div class="unit-num" style="color:var(--accent3)">Unit 3</div>
  <h2>Basic Accounting Process: Journal, Ledger & Trial Balance</h2>
</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m5">5 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>State the Accounting Equation and explain with an example.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <div class="formula">Assets = Liabilities + Capital (Owner's Equity)</div>
    <strong>Example Transactions:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Transaction</th><th>Assets</th><th>=</th><th>Liabilities</th><th>+</th><th>Capital</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Start business with ₹5,000 cash</td><td>5,000</td><td>=</td><td>0</td><td>+</td><td>5,000</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Buy furniture ₹2,000 cash</td><td>Cash 3,000 + Furn 2,000 = 5,000</td><td>=</td><td>0</td><td>+</td><td>5,000</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Purchase goods ₹3,000 on credit</td><td>8,000</td><td>=</td><td>3,000</td><td>+</td><td>5,000</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Paid ₹1,000 rent</td><td>7,000</td><td>=</td><td>3,000</td><td>+</td><td>4,000</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="tip-box">The equation ALWAYS balances. Every transaction has TWO effects (Double Entry).</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">2</div>What is the Double Entry System? State its rules of Debit and Credit.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Double Entry System:</span> Developed in 15th century Italy by <strong>Luca Pacioli</strong>. Every transaction has <strong>two aspects</strong> – both are recorded (one as Debit, one as Credit).<br><br>
    <strong>Rules of Debit (Dr.) and Credit (Cr.):</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Account Type</th><th>Debit (Dr.)</th><th>Credit (Cr.)</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Assets</td><td>Increase ↑</td><td>Decrease ↓</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Liabilities</td><td>Decrease ↓</td><td>Increase ↑</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Capital / Owner's Equity</td><td>Decrease ↓</td><td>Increase ↑</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Expenses / Losses</td><td>Increase ↑</td><td>Decrease ↓</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Revenue / Gains</td><td>Decrease ↓</td><td>Increase ↑</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Traditional Rule (Golden Rules):</strong><br>
    Personal A/c: Debit the receiver, Credit the giver<br>
    Real A/c: Debit what comes in, Credit what goes out<br>
    Nominal A/c: Debit all expenses/losses, Credit all incomes/gains</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">3</div>Classify accounts into Personal, Real, and Nominal with examples.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Type</th><th>Relates to</th><th>Examples</th><th>Golden Rule</th></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Personal A/c</strong></td><td>Persons (individuals, firms, companies)</td><td>Debtors A/c, Creditors A/c, Bank A/c, Capital A/c</td><td>Dr. the Receiver / Cr. the Giver</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Real A/c</strong></td><td>Assets (tangible and intangible)</td><td>Cash A/c, Furniture A/c, Building A/c, Goodwill A/c</td><td>Dr. what Comes In / Cr. what Goes Out</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Nominal A/c</strong></td><td>Expenses, losses, gains, revenues</td><td>Salary A/c, Rent A/c, Sales A/c, Commission Received A/c</td><td>Dr. all Expenses/Losses / Cr. all Incomes/Gains</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">4</div>What is Trial Balance? State its objectives and limitations.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Trial Balance</span> is a statement prepared by listing all ledger account balances (Debit and Credit) to check <strong>arithmetical accuracy</strong>. If total Debits = total Credits, the books are arithmetically correct.<br><br>
    <strong>Objectives:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Check arithmetical accuracy of ledger postings</li>
      <li>Basis for preparing final accounts (P&L, Balance Sheet)</li>
      <li>Helps detect certain errors (omissions, wrong posting of amounts)</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>Limitations (Errors NOT detected by Trial Balance):</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Error of <em>omission</em> – transaction not recorded at all (both sides missing)</li>
      <li>Error of <em>commission</em> – correct amount posted to wrong account</li>
      <li>Error of <em>principle</em> – revenue treated as capital or vice versa</li>
      <li><em>Compensating errors</em> – two errors that cancel each other out</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>Errors DETECTED by Trial Balance:</strong> Posting to wrong side (Dr./Cr.), error in balancing an account, error in carry forward of totals, item omitted from one subsidiary book.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m10">10 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>Explain the Journalizing Process with a worked example (format of Journal).</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <strong>Journal</strong> is the book of <em>original entry</em> where transactions are first recorded, showing which account is Debited and which is Credited.<br><br>
    <strong>Format of Journal:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Date</th><th>Particulars</th><th>L.F.</th><th style="text-align:right">Dr. Amount (₹)</th><th style="text-align:right">Cr. Amount (₹)</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Apr 1</td><td>Cash Account &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dr.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;To Capital Account<br><em>(Being business started with cash)</em></td><td>—</td><td style="text-align:right">50,000</td><td style="text-align:right">50,000</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Apr 2</td><td>Purchase Account &nbsp;&nbsp;Dr.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;To Cash Account<br><em>(Being goods purchased for cash)</em></td><td>—</td><td style="text-align:right">16,000</td><td style="text-align:right">16,000</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Apr 3</td><td>Rent Account &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dr.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;To Cash Account<br><em>(Being rent paid)</em></td><td>—</td><td style="text-align:right">2,000</td><td style="text-align:right">2,000</td></tr>
    </table>
    <br>
    <strong>Steps in Journalizing:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Step 1: Identify the two accounts affected</li>
      <li>Step 2: Classify each account (Personal/Real/Nominal)</li>
      <li>Step 3: Apply the Golden Rule to determine Dr./Cr.</li>
      <li>Step 4: Record the entry with a narration in brackets</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">2</div>Explain Ledger Posting and how to balance an account. Show the T-Account format.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <strong>Ledger</strong> is the <em>principal book of accounts</em>. Accounts are prepared here based on journal entries. Each account shows all transactions affecting it.<br><br>
    <strong>T-Account Format:</strong>
    <div class="diagram" style="font-family:'Courier New',monospace; font-size:0.88rem; color:var(--text);">
      <pre style="color:var(--text); background:transparent;">
Dr.          CASH ACCOUNT              Cr.
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Date | Particulars     | Amount  | Date | Particulars     | Amount
─────|─────────────────|─────────|──────|─────────────────|────────
Apr1 | To Capital A/c  | 50,000  | Apr2 | By Purchase A/c | 16,000
Apr16| To Commission   |  1,200  | Apr3 | By Rent A/c     |  2,000
Apr28| To Sales A/c    | 12,000  | Apr30| By Creditors    | 11,000
     |                 |         | Apr30| By Bal. c/d     | 34,200
─────|─────────────────|─────────|──────|─────────────────|────────
     | Total           | 63,200  |      | Total           | 63,200
May1 | To Balance b/d  | 34,200  |      |                 |
      </pre>
    </div>
    <strong>Steps to balance a Ledger Account:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Total both sides (Dr. and Cr.)</li>
      <li>Find the difference → this is the <em>balance</em></li>
      <li>Write the balance on the <em>smaller side</em> as "By Balance c/d" (if Dr. > Cr.) OR "To Balance c/d" (if Cr. > Dr.)</li>
      <li>Both sides now equal. Bring down balance to next period as "To Balance b/d" or "By Balance b/d"</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m20">20 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>Explain the complete Accounting Cycle with a diagram.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    The <span class="key-term">Accounting Cycle</span> is the complete sequence of steps followed in accounting from source documents to final financial statements.<br><br>
    <div class="diagram">
      <div class="diagram-title">The Accounting Cycle (8 Steps)</div>
