<div id="unit4" class="unit-header" style="border-left-color: var(--accent4);">
  <div class="unit-num" style="color:var(--accent4)">Unit 4</div>
  <h2>Preparation and Analysis of Final Accounts</h2>
</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m5">5 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>What is a Trading Account? State the formula for Gross Profit.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Trading Account</span> is the <em>first step</em> in preparing final accounts. It shows the result of buying and selling goods – either a <strong>Gross Profit or Gross Loss</strong>.<br><br>
    <div class="formula">
      Gross Profit = Net Sales Revenue − Cost of Goods Sold<br>
      Cost of Goods Sold = Opening Stock + Net Purchases + Direct Expenses − Closing Stock<br>
      Net Sales = Cash Sales + Credit Sales − Sales Returns<br>
      Net Purchases = Gross Purchases − Purchase Returns
    </div>
    <strong>Trading Account Format (T-Form):</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Dr. Side (Debit)</th><th>Cr. Side (Credit)</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Opening Stock</td><td>Sales (Net)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Net Purchases (Cash + Credit − Returns)</td><td>Closing Stock</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Direct Expenses (Wages, Carriage Inward, Freight, Power)</td><td></td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Gross Profit c/d</strong> (if Sales > Cost)</td><td><strong>Gross Loss c/d</strong> (if Cost > Sales)</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">2</div>What is a Profit and Loss Account? What items are Debited and Credited?</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Profit & Loss Account</span> shows the <strong>Net Profit or Net Loss</strong> after accounting for all operating and non-operating expenses and incomes.<br><br>
    <div class="formula">Net Profit = Gross Profit + Other Incomes − All Expenses (indirect)</div>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Debited (Expenses) in P&L</th><th>Credited (Income) in P&L</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Salaries, Rent, Advertisement</td><td>Gross Profit b/d</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Depreciation, Bad Debts</td><td>Dividend received, Interest received</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Stationery, Miscellaneous Expenses</td><td>Commission received</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Provision for Doubtful Debts</td><td>Profit on sale of fixed assets</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Insurance, Legal Charges</td><td>Transfer fee, Interest on drawings</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">3</div>What is a Balance Sheet? State its components.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Balance Sheet</span> is a <em>Position Statement</em> that shows the financial position of a business on a <strong>specific date</strong>. It is NOT a period statement – it is a snapshot.<br><br>
    <div class="formula">Assets = Liabilities + Owner's Equity (Capital)</div>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Liabilities Side</th><th>Assets Side</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Shareholders' Funds (Capital, Reserves)</td><td>Fixed Assets (Land, Building, Machinery)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Long-term Liabilities (Debentures, Loans)</td><td>Investments</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Current Liabilities (Creditors, Bills Payable)</td><td>Current Assets (Stock, Debtors, Cash, Bank)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Provisions (for Tax, Dividend)</td><td>Miscellaneous Expenditure (Preliminary exp.)</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="tip-box">Balance Sheet items are classified as: Fixed Assets, Current Assets, Investments, Long-term Liabilities, Current Liabilities, Shareholders' Funds.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">4</div>Explain Depreciation and its treatment in accounts.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Depreciation</span> is the <em>reduction in the value of a fixed asset</em> due to use, wear and tear, passage of time, or obsolescence.<br><br>
    <strong>Treatment:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Depreciation is <strong>debited to P&L Account</strong> (it is an expense)</li>
      <li>The asset's value in the Balance Sheet is shown as: <em>Original Cost − Accumulated Depreciation</em></li>
    </ul>
    <div class="formula">Book Value of Asset = Historical Cost − Accumulated Depreciation</div>
    <strong>Methods:</strong> Straight Line Method (SLM), Written Down Value (WDV) Method. Depreciation is a <em>non-cash expense</em>.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">5</div>What are Adjustment Entries? Name the main types.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Adjustment Entries</span> are entries passed at the end of the accounting period to ensure the financial statements reflect the <em>true and fair view</em>.<br><br>
    <strong>Types of Adjustment Entries:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Type</th><th>Treatment in P&L</th><th>Treatment in B/S</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Closing Stock</td><td>Credit to Trading A/c</td><td>Current Asset</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Depreciation</td><td>Debit to P&L A/c</td><td>Reduce asset value</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bad Debts</td><td>Debit to P&L A/c</td><td>Reduce Debtors</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Provision for Doubtful Debts</td><td>Debit to P&L A/c</td><td>Deduct from Debtors</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Outstanding Expenses</td><td>Add to expense in P&L</td><td>Current Liability</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Prepaid Expenses</td><td>Deduct from expense in P&L</td><td>Current Asset</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Accrued Income</td><td>Add to income in P&L</td><td>Current Asset</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Income Received in Advance</td><td>Deduct from income in P&L</td><td>Current Liability</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m10">10 Marks</span><hr></div>

