<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m20">20 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>Explain all Adjustment Entries in detail with their treatment in Final Accounts. Also explain the need for accounting information and its users.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <strong>I. Need for Accounting Information:</strong><br>
    Stakeholders need accounting information for planning, controlling, and decision-making. Two categories:
    <ul class="list">
      <li><em>Internal Users:</em> Top, middle, lower management – for operational decisions</li>
      <li><em>External Users:</em> Investors (ROI), Creditors (solvency), Banks (creditworthiness), Government (tax compliance), Customers (continuity)</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>II. Types of Accounting Information:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>P&L Account → Profit/Loss information (Is cost of sales reasonable? Can selling price be increased?)</li>
      <li>Balance Sheet → Financial position (Are invested funds safe? Is return adequate?)</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>III. All Adjustment Entries – Detailed Treatment:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>#</th><th>Adjustment</th><th>Journal Entry</th><th>P&L Effect</th><th>B/S Effect</th></tr>
      <tr><td>1</td><td>Closing Stock</td><td>Closing Stock A/c Dr. / To Trading A/c Cr.</td><td>Credit in Trading A/c</td><td>Current Asset</td></tr>
      <tr><td>2</td><td>Depreciation</td><td>Depreciation A/c Dr. / To Asset A/c Cr.</td><td>Debit to P&L</td><td>Reduce asset</td></tr>
      <tr><td>3</td><td>Bad Debts</td><td>Bad Debts A/c Dr. / To Debtors A/c Cr.</td><td>Debit to P&L</td><td>Reduce Debtors</td></tr>
      <tr><td>4</td><td>Provision for Doubtful Debts</td><td>P&L A/c Dr. / To Provision A/c Cr.</td><td>Debit to P&L</td><td>Deduct from Debtors (liability side provision)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>5</td><td>Outstanding Expenses</td><td>Expense A/c Dr. / To Outstanding Exp A/c Cr.</td><td>Add to relevant expense</td><td>Current Liability</td></tr>
      <tr><td>6</td><td>Prepaid Expenses</td><td>Prepaid Exp A/c Dr. / To Expense A/c Cr.</td><td>Deduct from expense</td><td>Current Asset</td></tr>
      <tr><td>7</td><td>Accrued Income</td><td>Accrued Income A/c Dr. / To Income A/c Cr.</td><td>Add to income</td><td>Current Asset</td></tr>
      <tr><td>8</td><td>Income Received in Advance</td><td>Income A/c Dr. / To Income Received in Adv. Cr.</td><td>Deduct from income</td><td>Current Liability</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Key Rule:</strong> Prepaid Expenses = ASSET (already paid, benefit not yet received)<br>Outstanding Expenses = LIABILITY (benefit received, not yet paid)<br>Accrued Income = ASSET (earned but not received)<br>Income Received in Advance = LIABILITY (received but not yet earned)</div>
    <strong>IV. Forensic Accounting in Final Accounts:</strong><br>
    Forensic Accounting helps detect manipulation in final accounts. Uses: Bank frauds detection (Nirav Modi case), SEBI investigations for insider trading, shell company detection, insolvency proceedings.
  </div>
</div>

