<div id="unit5" class="unit-header" style="border-left-color: #a78bfa;">
  <div class="unit-num" style="color:#a78bfa">Unit 5</div>
  <h2>Statement of Changes in Financial Position (Cash Flow Statement)</h2>
</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m5">5 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>What is SCFP? Why is it needed?</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">SCFP (Statement of Changes in Financial Position)</span> is a statement that identifies the <strong>sources and uses of funds</strong> during a given accounting period. It shows changes in assets, liabilities, and owner's equity between two balance sheet dates.<br><br>
    <strong>Why Needed?</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>P&L and Balance Sheet do NOT show where money came from and where it went</li>
      <li>A company can make profits yet face cash crunch (profits locked in assets)</li>
      <li>Shows whether short-term liabilities can be met (liquidity analysis)</li>
      <li>Reveals financial structure changes</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>Two Types of SCFP:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li><strong>Working Capital Basis:</strong> → Funds Flow Statement</li>
      <li><strong>Cash Basis:</strong> → Cash Flow Statement</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">2</div>What is Working Capital? What are sources and uses of funds?</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <div class="formula">Working Capital = Current Assets − Current Liabilities</div>
    <strong>Sources of Funds (Inflows – Increase Working Capital):</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Funds from operations (Net Profit + Non-cash charges like Depreciation)</li>
      <li>Issue of shares or debentures</li>
      <li>Long-term borrowings (loans)</li>
      <li>Sale of fixed assets</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>Uses/Application of Funds (Outflows – Decrease Working Capital):</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Purchase of fixed assets</li>
      <li>Repayment of long-term loans</li>
      <li>Redemption of debentures/preference shares</li>
      <li>Payment of dividends (if treated as current liability)</li>
      <li>Payment of tax (if treated as current liability)</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="tip-box"><strong>Non-Fund Items (do NOT affect Working Capital):</strong> Depreciation, Provision for Tax/Dividend (if treated as long-term), Bonus shares issued, Transfer to reserves from profits.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">3</div>What is a Cash Flow Statement? State its components per AS-3.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Cash Flow Statement</span> shows the <strong>sources and uses of cash</strong> during a period. It tracks cash inflows and outflows.<br><br>
    <strong>Three Activities per AS-3 / IND AS-7:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Activity</th><th>Examples of Inflows</th><th>Examples of Outflows</th></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Operating</strong></td><td>Cash sales, receipts from debtors</td><td>Cash purchases, payments to creditors, wages, taxes</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Investing</strong></td><td>Sale of fixed assets, sale of investments</td><td>Purchase of fixed assets, purchase of investments</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Financing</strong></td><td>Issue of shares, borrowing loans</td><td>Repayment of loans, payment of dividends, interest paid</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="formula">Net Increase/Decrease in Cash = CFO + CFI + CFF<br>
Closing Cash = Opening Cash + Net Change in Cash</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">4</div>What are the uses of Cash Flow Analysis?</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <ul class="list">
      <li><strong>Efficient cash management:</strong> Helps plan cash requirements and avoid cash shortages</li>
      <li><strong>Reveals cash movement:</strong> Shows actual cash in and out (unlike accrual-based P&L)</li>
      <li><strong>Internal financial management:</strong> Helps management decide timing of payments and receipts</li>
      <li><strong>Reveals success/failure of cash planning:</strong> Compare planned vs actual cash flows</li>
      <li><strong>Liquidity assessment:</strong> Can the firm meet its short-term obligations?</li>
      <li><strong>Investment decisions:</strong> Shows ability to fund new projects from internal sources</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

