<div id="unit6" class="unit-header" style="border-left-color: var(--accent3);">
  <div class="unit-num" style="color:var(--accent3)">Unit 6</div>
  <h2>Ratio Analysis</h2>
</div>

<div class="warn-box"><strong>📌 Ratio Formula Quick Reference – Memorise These!</strong><br>
Current Ratio = CA/CL | Quick Ratio = (CA−Stock)/CL | Debt-Equity = LTD/SHF | GP Ratio = GP/Sales×100 | NP Ratio = NP/Sales×100 | ROE = NP/Equity×100 | EPS = (NP−PrefDiv)/No.of shares</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m5">5 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>What is Ratio Analysis? State its objectives and limitations.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Ratio Analysis</span> is the <em>quantitative interpretation</em> of a company's financial performance by establishing relationships between items in financial statements.<br><br>
    <strong>Objectives:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Measure financial soundness (solvency)</li>
      <li>Measure profitability</li>
      <li>Judge operational efficiency</li>
      <li>Indicate trends over time</li>
      <li>Assess growth potential</li>
      <li>Enable inter-firm and intra-firm comparison</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>Users of Financial Ratios:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li><em>Trade Creditors:</em> Short-term liquidity (Current Ratio)</li>
      <li><em>Long-term Lenders/Banks:</em> Long-term solvency (Debt-Equity Ratio)</li>
      <li><em>Investors:</em> Profitability and EPS (Net Profit Ratio, P/E Ratio)</li>
      <li><em>Management:</em> All ratios for overall performance control</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>Limitations:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Based on historical data – may not reflect future</li>
      <li>Inflation distorts comparisons over years</li>
      <li>Different accounting policies make inter-firm comparison unreliable</li>
      <li>Ratios are only as good as the underlying data</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">2</div>Explain Liquidity Ratios (Short-term Solvency Ratios).</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    Liquidity Ratios measure the ability of a firm to meet its <strong>short-term obligations</strong>.<br><br>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Ratio</th><th>Formula</th><th>Ideal Ratio</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Current Ratio</strong></td><td>Current Assets / Current Liabilities</td><td>2:1</td><td>Can meet short-term debts twice over</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Quick/Acid-Test Ratio</strong></td><td>(CA − Stock − Prepaid Expenses) / CL</td><td>1:1</td><td>Can meet short-term debts without selling stock</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Absolute Liquidity Ratio</strong></td><td>(Cash + Marketable Securities) / CL</td><td>0.5:1</td><td>Immediate cash availability</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="tip-box"><strong>Quick Assets</strong> = Current Assets − Stock − Prepaid Expenses (items NOT quickly convertible to cash)</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">3</div>Explain Long-term Solvency (Leverage) Ratios.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Ratio</th><th>Formula</th><th>What it Measures</th></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Debt-Equity Ratio</strong></td><td>Long-term Debt / Shareholders' Funds</td><td>Proportion of debt vs equity in financing</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Shareholders' Equity Ratio</strong></td><td>Shareholders' Equity / Total Tangible Assets</td><td>Financial strength; higher = stronger</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Proprietary Ratio</strong></td><td>Proprietors' Funds / Total Assets</td><td>Proportion of assets financed by owners</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Capital Gearing Ratio</strong></td><td>Fixed Interest Securities / Equity Shareholders' Funds</td><td>Highly geared = more debt, more risk</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Interest Cover</strong></td><td>EBIT / Interest Charges</td><td>Times interest can be paid from profits</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Debt Service Coverage Ratio (DSCR)</strong></td><td>Net Cash Accruals / (Interest + Loan Repayment)</td><td>Ability to service total debt obligations</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="warn-box">Good solvency ratio = 0.5 or above. A high debt-equity ratio = high financial risk (highly geared company).</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">4</div>Explain Activity/Turnover Ratios.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    Activity Ratios measure how <em>efficiently</em> a firm uses its assets to generate sales (turnover).<br><br>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Ratio</th><th>Formula</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Inventory/Stock Turnover</strong></td><td>Cost of Goods Sold / Average Stock</td><td>How many times stock is turned into sales per year</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Debtors Turnover</strong></td><td>Net Credit Sales / Average Debtors</td><td>How efficiently credit is collected</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Debtor Collection Period</strong></td><td>365 / Debtors Turnover Ratio</td><td>Average days to collect from debtors</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Creditors Turnover</strong></td><td>Net Credit Purchases / Average Creditors</td><td>Speed of payment to creditors</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Working Capital Turnover</strong></td><td>Net Sales / Working Capital</td><td>Revenue generated per rupee of working capital</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Fixed Assets Turnover</strong></td><td>Net Sales / Fixed Assets</td><td>Revenue per rupee invested in fixed assets</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Total Assets Turnover</strong></td><td>Net Sales / Total Assets</td><td>Revenue per rupee of total assets</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Capital Turnover</strong></td><td>Net Sales / Capital Employed</td><td>Efficiency of capital use</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">5</div>Explain Profitability Ratios.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    Profitability Ratios measure a firm's ability to generate <strong>profit</strong> in relation to sales, assets, or equity.<br><br>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Ratio</th><th>Formula</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Gross Profit Ratio</strong></td><td>(GP / Net Sales) × 100</td><td>Profit % after cost of goods sold</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Net Profit Ratio</strong></td><td>(Net Profit / Net Sales) × 100</td><td>Overall profitability after all expenses</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Operating Profit Ratio</strong></td><td>(Operating Profit / Net Sales) × 100</td><td>Profitability from core operations</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Operating Ratio</strong></td><td>((COGS + Operating Expenses) / Net Sales) × 100</td><td>Cost efficiency; lower = better</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Return on Capital Employed (ROCE)</strong></td><td>(EBIT / Capital Employed) × 100</td><td>Return on total capital</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Return on Equity (ROE)</strong></td><td>(Net Profit / Shareholders' Equity) × 100</td><td>Return for equity shareholders</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Return on Total Assets</strong></td><td>(Net Profit after Tax / Total Assets) × 100</td><td>Efficient use of all assets</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="formula">Operating Profit = Net Profit + Non-operating Expenses − Non-operating Incomes</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m10">10 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>Explain Market Test Ratios (Investor Ratios).</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    Market Test Ratios are used by <strong>investors</strong> to assess a firm's market performance and returns.<br><br>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Ratio</th><th>Formula</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>EPS (Earnings Per Share)</strong></td><td>(Net Profit − Preference Dividend) / No. of Equity Shares</td><td>Profit earned per equity share</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>P/E Ratio (Price-Earnings)</strong></td><td>Market Price per Share / EPS</td><td>How much investors pay per ₹1 of earnings; higher = growth expectation</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Dividend Yield</strong></td><td>(Dividend per Share / Market Price) × 100</td><td>Return on investment via dividends</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Dividend Pay-out Ratio</strong></td><td>(Dividend per Share / EPS) × 100</td><td>% of earnings distributed as dividend</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Dividend Cover</strong></td><td>EPS / Dividend per Share</td><td>Times dividend is covered by earnings</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Book Value per Share</strong></td><td>Net Assets / No. of Equity Shares</td><td>Value of net assets backing each share</td></tr>
    </table>
    <strong>Example Calculation (from Unit 6):</strong><br>
    Preference Dividend = ₹27,000, Net Profit = ₹2,70,000, Equity Shares = 80,000, Market Price = ₹40
    <div class="formula">EPS = (2,70,000 − 27,000) / 80,000 = ₹3.04<br>
P/E Ratio = ₹40 / ₹3.04 = 13.16 : 1<br>
Dividend per share = 20% of ₹10 = ₹2<br>
Dividend Yield = (₹2 / ₹40) × 100 = 5%<br>
Dividend Pay-out = (₹2 / ₹3.04) × 100 = 66%</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m20">20 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>Explain in detail all categories of Ratios with formulas, ideal values, and their diagnostic/utility role in financial analysis.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <strong>I. Categories of Financial Ratios:</strong>
